---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Knowledge OS Product"
  description="A product-style view of Knowledge OS, the local-first operating system for signal intake, promotion gates, agent workflows, and reviewable artifacts."
  image="/knowledge-os/longform-infographic.png"
>
  <div class="container-wide">
    <section class="workbench-hero">
      <div class="panel workbench-hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Knowledge OS product view</p>
        <h1>Knowledge OS keeps signals, memory, agents, and artifacts in one inspectable loop.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          A local-first operating system for capturing source material, deciding what deserves trust, routing agent workflows, and producing reviewable outputs.
        </p>
        <div class="pill-row">
          <span class="pill blue">Local-first</span>
          <span class="pill sage">Source-aware</span>
          <span class="pill plum">Human-reviewed</span>
          <span class="pill orange">Agent-assisted</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="panel workbench-card">
        <div class="sticky-note">
          <span class="pill blue">System promise</span>
          <strong>Keep the loop visible.</strong>
          <p>Every run should leave a trace. Every promotion should be reviewable. Every artifact should point back to source material.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-dark">
          <div class="diagram-node"><div class="eyebrow">Sources</div><strong>Signals</strong></div>
          <div class="diagram-arrow">-&gt;</div>
          <div class="diagram-node"><div class="eyebrow">Core</div><strong>Knowledge</strong></div>
          <div class="diagram-arrow">-&gt;</div>
          <div class="diagram-node"><div class="eyebrow">Surfaces</div><strong>Outputs</strong></div>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Core Capabilities</h2>
      <div class="feature-grid">
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill blue">Intake</span>
          <h3>Signal capture</h3>
          <p>Bring in public posts, newsletters, agent sessions, source docs, and working notes without flattening everything into the same kind of memory.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill sage">Governance</span>
          <h3>Promotion gates</h3>
          <p>Review, source-check, and intentionally promote material before it becomes durable knowledge or future-agent context.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill plum">Review</span>
          <h3>Human cockpit</h3>
          <p>Keep review queues, current state, and next actions visible in plain files so the human operator remains in control.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="feature-card">
          <span class="pill copper">Output</span>
          <h3>Artifact pipelines</h3>
          <p>Turn selected material into briefs, reply candidates, article seeds, run reports, and operating documentation.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Architecture</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The system is layered so raw capture, governed knowledge, agent workflows, and publishing surfaces can evolve independently.
      </p>
      <figure class="image-frame">
        <img src="/knowledge-os/layered-architecture.png" alt="Layered Knowledge OS architecture diagram." loading="lazy" />
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Modules</h2>
      <div class="proof-strip">
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill blue">Scout</span>
          <strong>X Signal Scout</strong>
          <p>Finds candidate conversations, preserves raw artifacts, and routes reply opportunities through review.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill sage">Desk</span>
          <strong>Knowledge Desk Copilot</strong>
          <p>Updates the human cockpit with newsletter intake, source queues, and current action state.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="proof-item">
          <span class="pill plum">Feedback</span>
          <strong>Engagement Radar</strong>
          <p>Connects posted outcomes, review decisions, and future selection rules into a learning loop.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <h2>Long-Form System View</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        This version is intentionally product-like: it shows the named system, the operating zones, and how a concrete workflow such as Engagement Radar fits inside the wider Knowledge OS.
      </p>
      <figure class="image-frame">
        <img src="/knowledge-os/longform-infographic.png" alt="Long-form Knowledge OS infographic showing source, memory, process, and artifact layers." loading="lazy" />
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="section-band">
      <div class="callout">
        <p class="eyebrow">Status</p>
        <h2>This is an active internal system, not packaged software.</h2>
        <p>
          The product-style framing is useful for explaining the system shape. It should only become the primary public page if we want Knowledge OS to read as a flagship product direction.
        </p>
        <p><a href="/knowledge-os-proof/">Compare the proof-page version &rarr;</a></p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
